# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atmosphere-of-earth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In 2026, astronomers announced the discovery of a thin atmosphere around 2002 XV93, making it likely the first TNO after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere, and defying expectations that it should be too small to hold onto an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] With a surface pressure of 100–200 nanobars (roughly 5 million to 10 million times thinner than Earth's atmosphere or 50 to 100 times thinner than Pluto's atmosphere), it is predicted that 2002 XV93 should lose all of its atmosphere in 100 to 1,000 years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The existence of 2002 XV93's atmosphere suggests it was recently replenished, either by a comet impact or outgassing via cryovolcanic eruptions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The composition of the atmosphere is unknown, but it is thought to contain either nitrogen, argon, or methane.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 was discovered on 10 December 2002 (Universal Time; UT) by Palomar Observatory in California, United States.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] At that time, a team of astronomers led by Chad Trujillo and Michael E.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Brown were working in Palomar Observatory using its 1.2-m Samuel Oschin telescope, operating jointly with the Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking (NEAT) program.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The object's discovery was announced by the Minor Planet Center (MPC) on 5 January 2003.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Precovery observations of 2002 XV93 from Palomar Observatory were later identified in 2008, with the observations dating to 16 October 1990, 12 October 1991, and 28 September 1992.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] On 10 January 2024 (UT), 2002 XV93 passed in front of a magnitude-15.8 star in the constellation Auriga, causing it to briefly dim from Earth for up to 20 seconds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] This event, known as a stellar occultation, was predicted and observed in Japan by a team of astronomers led by Ko Arimatsu of the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Telescopes were stationed at Kyoto University, Kiso Observatory, Fukushima Prefecture, and Okayama Observatory, but only the first three sites detected the occultation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] All detections showed that the star faded gradually (lasting up to 1.5 seconds) rather than abruptly during the occultation, revealing that 2002 XV93 had an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The discovery was announced on 4 May 2026, making 2002 XV93 likely the first trans-Neptunian object after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] This object is currently known by its minor planet provisional designation 2002 XV93, given by the MPC upon its discovery.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The MPC gave it the minor planet number of 612533 on 28 March 2022.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] According to naming guidelines by the International Astronomical Union's Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature, trans-Neptunian objects classified as plutinos, such as 2002 XV93, should be given mythological names related to the underworld.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Since 2002 XV93 received its minor planet number less than 10 years ago, only the discoverer has the privilege of naming it.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In an interview with *Reuters* on 4 May 2026, Arimatsu remarked that the current designation of 2002 XV93 is unmemorable and advocated for a name related to Okinawan mythology, such as Amamikyu (/əˈmɑːmikjuː/).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Brown, who was involved in Palomar Observatory's discovery of 2002 XV93, commented that the object did not get named because it had no known remarkable properties before Arimatsu's discovery of its atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 orbits the Sun's barycenter with a semi-major axis of 39.3 astronomical units (AU), putting it in the Kuiper belt beyond Neptune's orbit.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 takes 246 years to complete one orbit, which places it in a 2:3 mean-motion resonance with Neptune.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] For every two revolutions it makes around the Sun, Neptune makes exactly three.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] It is therefore a member of the plutinos, a large population of trans-Neptunian objects (TNOs) named after its largest member Pluto.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93's orbit is elliptical, with an orbital eccentricity of 0.12, and inclined by 13° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Its distance from the Sun ranges from 34.4 AU at perihelion to 44.2 AU at aphelion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 will come to perihelion in March 2070.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Due to gravitational perturbations by the giant planets, the orbital elements of 2002 XV93 vary over time.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Simulations of 2002 XV93's orbit show that in 10 million years, its semi-major axis can fluctuate between 39.1–39.9 AU, eccentricity between 0.10–0.15, and inclination between 12.5–13.9°.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Observations of a stellar occultation in 2024 show that 2002 XV93 has a radius of 235+22 −15 km, or a diameter of 470+44 −30 km, assuming it has a spherical shape.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] For comparison, 2002 XV93 is about one-seventh the diameter of Earth's moon and about one-fifth the diameter of Pluto.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The mass, bulk density, and shape of 2002 XV93 are unknown, though they can be inferred from those of other similarly-sized TNOs like Huya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] A 2026 study by Arimatsu and colleagues assumed 2002 XV93 had a bulk density between 1.0 and 1.5 g/cm3, similar to those of Huya and Pluto's moon Charon, respectively.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The surface gravity of 2002 XV93 is estimated to be around 100 times weaker than Earth's.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Arimatsu and colleagues expect that 2002 XV93 has a non-spherical shape due to its relatively small diameter of a few hundred kilometres.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The rotation period of 2002 XV93 is unknown and it has not yet been studied via light curves, according to the *Asteroid Lightcurve Database*.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Some astronomers, including Noemi Pinilla-Alonso and Michael E.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Brown, previously suggested that 2002 XV93 could be theoretically large enough to become spherical and be possibly a dwarf planet, based on a larger diameter estimate from 2012.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] This outdated estimate had 2002 XV93 549.2+21.7 −23.0 km in diameter, based on mid- to far-infrared measurements of its thermal emission by the Herschel Space Observatory and Spitzer Space Telescope.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Measurements of 2002 XV93's visible brightness and infrared thermal radiation suggest that its surface is dark, with a very low geometric albedo of 0.040+0.020 −0.015.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] However, this estimate was made in 2012 using a visible-light (V-band) absolute magnitude 5.42±0.46 and thermal emission-derived diameter of 549.2+21.7 −23.0 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] More recent measurements have since found a brighter V-band absolute magnitude of 4.73 and a smaller diameter of 470+44 −30 km, which should indicate a higher albedo for 2002 XV93.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] However, as of May 2026, no peer-reviewed studies have recalculated 2002 XV93's albedo using newer measurements of its absolute magnitude and diameter.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Telescopic observations in visible light show that the surface color of 2002 XV93 is gray, similar to some centaurs and Kuiper belt objects including Achlys and 2004 EW95.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Due to 2002 XV93's great distance from the Sun, its surface temperature averages around 47 K (−226.2 °C; −375.1 °F), cold enough to freeze substances like water into solid ice.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Near-infrared spectroscopy by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) has shown that the surface of 2002 XV93 is rich in water ice, in both amorphous and crystalline phases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The abundance of water ice in 2002 XV93's surface is indicated by the presence of absorption bands at wavelengths of 1.5, 2.0, 3.0, and 4.5 μm in the object's near-infrared spectrum, alongside a reflectance peak at 3.1 μm due to crystalline water ice.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In the Kuiper belt, crystalline water ice tends to transform into amorphous water ice due to irradiation by cosmic rays, though both phases are expected to be in equilibrium (i.e. amounts of crystalline and amorphous water ice remain constant).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 shares its water ice-rich surface composition with other TNOs, including the plutinos 2004 EW95 and 2003 UZ413.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] These TNOs are classified as "prominent water"-type or "Bowl"-type TNOs, because their near-infrared spectra display a significant bowl-shaped water ice absorption band at the wavelength of 3.0 μm.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Besides water, JWST has detected frozen carbon dioxide (CO 2) on 2002 XV93's surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] JWST has also detected trace amounts of 13CO 2 (a rare isotopologue of CO 2).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In observations from 2022 and 2024, JWST found no signs of hypervolatile compounds such as methane, nitrogen, and carbon monoxide (which can sublimate into gases at 2002 XV93's temperature).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The lack of hypervolatiles on 2002 XV93's surface suggests that most of them had already sublimated and escaped into space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In May 2026, a research team led by Ko Arimatsu announced the discovery of a thin atmosphere around 2002 XV93, making it possibly the first TNO after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The atmosphere was inferred from observations of a stellar occultation in January 2024, when 2002 XV93 passed in front of a star and dimmed its light gradually (lasting 1.5 seconds) instead of abruptly, indicating refraction by an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The gradual disappearance and reappearance of the star was observed to occur within radii of 230 to 270 km (140 to 170 mi) from 2002 XV93's center.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Alternate explanations for this gradual fading, such as a ring system or a shell of dust, are considered unlikely.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] At this pressure, 2002 XV93's atmosphere is dense enough (>0.001 nanobar) that its gas molecules can collide amongst themselves, making it a true atmosphere rather than an exosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] No other TNO besides Pluto is known to have an atmospheric pressure this high.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] However, it is unclear how the density of 2002 XV93's atmosphere changes with altitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The composition 2002 XV93's atmosphere is unknown, and there are competing hypotheses for it.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] One possible composition is methane, a common hypervolatile found in TNOs.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] In occultation observations, 2002 XV93's atmosphere appeared to show a sudden change in refraction at a certain altitude, suggesting that it has a thermal inversion caused by upper-atmospheric heating of trace methane gas (similar to Pluto).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] However, JWST observed the object after its 2024 occultation and found no signs of methane and carbon monoxide gas, suggesting they do not make up much of its atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] If these gases exist over a large altitude range, their partial pressures at 2002 XV93's surface must be less than 0.0003 nanobars (0.3 picobars).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] However, it remains possible that a low-altitude atmosphere of pure methane could exist.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Using these JWST observations, a research team headed by Ian Wong proposed that 2002 XV93's atmosphere could contain either nitrogen, argon, or any other gas that couldn't be detected by JWST.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The discovery of an atmosphere around 2002 XV93 was unexpected because the object is too small to have a surface gravity strong enough to theoretically hold on to an atmosphere over the age of the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Physical models predict that 2002 XV93 should lose all of its atmosphere within 100 to 1,000 years via Jeans escape.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] The present-day existence of 2002 XV93's atmosphere implies that it was recently replenished, though the cause is unknown.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Sublimation of volatile ices on 2002 XV93's surface is unlikely, because it was not detected in earlier JWST observations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/612533-2002-xv93] Arimatsu's team hypothesized that 2002 XV93 obtained its atmosphere via either an impact by a hundred-meter-radius comet, or outgassing by cryovolcanic eruptions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] In physics, **absorption** of electromagnetic radiation is how matter (typically electrons bound in atoms) takes up a photon's energy—and so transforms electromagnetic energy into internal energy of the absorber (for example, thermal energy).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] A notable effect of the absorption of electromagnetic radiation is attenuation of the radiation; attenuation is the gradual reduction of the intensity of light waves as they propagate through a medium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Although the absorption of waves does not usually depend on their intensity (linear absorption), in certain conditions (optics) the medium's transparency changes by a factor that varies as a function of wave intensity, and saturable absorption (or nonlinear absorption) occurs.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Many approaches can potentially quantify radiation absorption, with key examples following.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] All these quantities measure, at least to some extent, how well a medium absorbs radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Which among them practitioners use varies by field and technique, often due simply to the convention.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] The absorbance of an object quantifies how much of the incident light is absorbed by it (instead of being reflected or refracted).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] This may be related to other properties of the object through the Beer–Lambert law.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Precise measurements of the absorbance at many wavelengths allow the identification of a substance via absorption spectroscopy, where a sample is illuminated from one side, and the intensity of the light that exits from the sample in every direction is measured.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] A few examples of absorption are ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy, infrared spectroscopy, and X-ray absorption spectroscopy.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Understanding and measuring the absorption of electromagnetic radiation has a variety of applications.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is employed as an analytical chemistry tool to determine the presence of a particular substance in a sample and, in many cases, to quantify the amount of the substance present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Infrared and ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy are particularly common in analytical applications.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in studies of molecular and atomic physics, astronomical spectroscopy and remote sensing.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] There is a wide range of experimental approaches for measuring absorption spectra.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The most common arrangement is to direct a generated beam of radiation at a sample and detect the intensity of the radiation that passes through it.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The transmitted energy can be used to calculate the absorption.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The source, sample arrangement and detection technique vary significantly depending on the frequency range and the purpose of the experiment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] A material's absorption spectrum is the fraction of incident radiation absorbed by the material over a range of frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The absorption spectrum is primarily determined by the atomic and molecular composition of the material.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Radiation is more likely to be absorbed at frequencies that match the energy difference between two quantum mechanical states of the molecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The absorption that occurs due to a transition between two states is referred to as an absorption line and a spectrum is typically composed of many lines.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The frequencies at which absorption lines occur, as well as their relative intensities, primarily depend on the electronic and molecular structure of the sample.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The frequencies will also depend on the interactions between molecules in the sample, the crystal structure in solids, and on several environmental factors (e.g., temperature, pressure, electric field, magnetic field).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The lines will also have a width and shape that are primarily determined by the spectral density or the density of states of the system.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption lines are typically classified by the nature of the quantum mechanical change induced in the molecule or atom.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Rotational lines, for instance, occur when the rotational state of a molecule is changed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Rotational lines are typically found in the microwave spectral region.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Vibrational lines correspond to changes in the vibrational state of the molecule and are typically found in the infrared region.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Electronic lines correspond to a change in the electronic state of an atom or molecule and are typically found in the visible and ultraviolet region.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] X-ray absorptions are associated with the excitation of inner shell electrons in atoms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] These changes can also be combined (e.g. rotation–vibration transitions), leading to new absorption lines at the combined energy of the two changes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The energy associated with the quantum mechanical change primarily determines the frequency of the absorption line but the frequency can be shifted by several types of interactions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Electric and magnetic fields can cause a shift.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Interactions with neighboring molecules can cause shifts.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For instance, absorption lines of the gas phase molecule can shift significantly when that molecule is in a liquid or solid phase and interacting more strongly with neighboring molecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The width and shape of absorption lines are determined by the instrument used for the observation, the material absorbing the radiation and the physical environment of that material.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] It is common for lines to have the shape of a Gaussian or Lorentzian distribution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] It is also common for a line to be described solely by its intensity and width instead of the entire shape being characterized.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The integrated intensity—obtained by integrating the area under the absorption line—is proportional to the amount of the absorbing substance present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The intensity is also related to the temperature of the substance and the quantum mechanical interaction between the radiation and the absorber.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] This interaction is quantified by the transition moment and depends on the particular lower state the transition starts from, and the upper state it is connected to.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The width of absorption lines may be determined by the spectrometer used to record it.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] A spectrometer has an inherent limit on how narrow a line it can resolve and so the observed width may be at this limit.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] If the width is larger than the resolution limit, then it is primarily determined by the environment of the absorber.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] A liquid or solid absorber, in which neighboring molecules strongly interact with one another, tends to have broader absorption lines than a gas.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Increasing the temperature or pressure of the absorbing material will also tend to increase the line width.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] It is also common for several neighboring transitions to be close enough to one another that their lines overlap and the resulting overall line is therefore broader yet.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption and transmission spectra represent equivalent information and one can be calculated from the other through a mathematical transformation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] A transmission spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is weakest because more light is transmitted through the sample.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] An absorption spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is strongest.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Emission is a process by which a substance releases energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Emission can occur at any frequency at which absorption can occur, and this allows the absorption lines to be determined from an emission spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The emission spectrum will typically have a quite different intensity pattern from the absorption spectrum, though, so the two are not equivalent.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The absorption spectrum can be calculated from the emission spectrum using Einstein coefficients.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The scattering and reflection spectra of a material are influenced by both its refractive index and its absorption spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] In an optical context, the absorption spectrum is typically quantified by the extinction coefficient, and the extinction and index coefficients are quantitatively related through the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Therefore, the absorption spectrum can be derived from a scattering or reflection spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] This typically requires simplifying assumptions or models, and so the derived absorption spectrum is an approximation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is useful in chemical analysis because of its specificity and its quantitative nature.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The specificity of absorption spectra allows compounds to be distinguished from one another in a mixture, making absorption spectroscopy useful in wide variety of applications.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For instance, Infrared gas analyzers can be used to detect pollutants in the air, distinguishing them from nitrogen, oxygen, water, and other expected constituents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The specificity also allows unknown samples to be identified by comparing a measured spectrum with a library of reference spectra.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] In many cases, qualitative information about a sample can be determined even if it is not in a library.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Infrared spectra, for instance, have characteristic absorption bands that indicate if carbon-hydrogen or carbon-oxygen bonds are present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] An absorption spectrum can be quantitatively related to the amount of material present using the Beer–Lambert law .
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Determining the absolute concentration of a compound requires knowledge of the compound's absorption coefficient.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The absorption coefficient for some compounds is available in reference sources, and it can also be determined by measuring the spectrum of a calibration standard with a known concentration of the target compound.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] One of the unique advantages of spectroscopy as an analytical technique is that measurements can be made without bringing the instrument and sample into contact.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Radiation that travels between a sample and an instrument will contain the spectral information, so the measurement can be made remotely.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Remote spectral sensing is valuable in many situations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For example, measurements can be made in toxic or hazardous environments without placing an operator or instrument at risk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Also, sample material does not have to be brought into contact with the instrument—preventing possible cross contamination.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Remote spectral measurements present several challenges compared to laboratory measurements.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The space in between the sample of interest and the instrument may also have spectral absorptions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] These absorptions can mask or confound the absorption spectrum of the sample.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] These background interferences may also vary over time.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The source of radiation in remote measurements is often an environmental source, such as sunlight or the thermal radiation from a warm object, and this makes it necessary to distinguish spectral absorption from changes in the source spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] To simplify these challenges, differential optical absorption spectroscopy has gained some popularity, as it focusses on differential absorption features and omits broad-band absorption such as aerosol extinction and extinction due to rayleigh scattering.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] This method is applied to ground-based, airborne, and satellite-based measurements.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Some ground-based methods provide the possibility to retrieve tropospheric and stratospheric trace gas profiles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Astronomical spectroscopy is a particularly significant type of remote spectral sensing.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] In this case, the objects and samples of interest are so distant from earth that electromagnetic radiation is the only means available to measure them.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Astronomical spectra contain both absorption and emission spectral information.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy has been particularly important for understanding interstellar clouds and determining that some of them contain molecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in the study of extrasolar planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Detection of extrasolar planets by transit photometry also measures their absorption spectrum and allows for the determination of the planet's atmospheric composition, temperature, pressure, and scale height, and hence allows also for the determination of the planet's mass.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Theoretical models, principally quantum mechanical models, allow for the absorption spectra of atoms and molecules to be related to other physical properties such as electronic structure, atomic or molecular mass, and molecular geometry.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Therefore, measurements of the absorption spectrum are used to determine these other properties.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Microwave spectroscopy, for example, allows for the determination of bond lengths and angles with high precision.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] In addition, spectral measurements can be used to determine the accuracy of theoretical predictions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For example, the Lamb shift measured in the hydrogen atomic absorption spectrum was not expected to exist at the time it was measured.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Its discovery spurred and guided the development of quantum electrodynamics, and measurements of the Lamb shift are now used to determine the fine-structure constant.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The most straightforward approach to absorption spectroscopy is to generate radiation with a source, measure a reference spectrum of that radiation with a detector and then re-measure the sample spectrum after placing the material of interest in between the source and detector.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The two measured spectra can then be combined to determine the material's absorption spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The reference spectrum will be affected in the same way, though, by these experimental conditions and therefore the combination yields the absorption spectrum of the material alone.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] A wide variety of radiation sources are employed in order to cover the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For spectroscopy, it is generally desirable for a source to cover a broad swath of wavelengths in order to measure a broad region of the absorption spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Some sources inherently emit a broad spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Examples of these include globars or other black body sources in the infrared, mercury lamps in the visible and ultraviolet, and X-ray tubes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] One recently developed, novel source of broad spectrum radiation is synchrotron radiation, which covers all of these spectral regions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Other radiation sources generate a narrow spectrum, but the emission wavelength can be tuned to cover a spectral range.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Examples of these include klystrons in the microwave region and lasers across the infrared, visible, and ultraviolet region (though not all lasers have tunable wavelengths).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The detector employed to measure the radiation power will also depend on the wavelength range of interest.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Most detectors are sensitive to a fairly broad spectral range and the sensor selected will often depend more on the sensitivity and noise requirements of a given measurement.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Examples of detectors common in spectroscopy include heterodyne receivers in the microwave, bolometers in the millimeter-wave and infrared, mercury cadmium telluride and other cooled semiconductor detectors in the infrared, and photodiodes and photomultiplier tubes in the visible and ultraviolet.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] If both the source and the detector cover a broad spectral region, then it is also necessary to introduce a means of resolving the wavelength of the radiation in order to determine the spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Often a spectrograph is used to spatially separate the wavelengths of radiation so that the power at each wavelength can be measured independently.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] It is also common to employ interferometry to determine the spectrum—Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy is a widely used implementation of this technique.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] Two other issues that must be considered in setting up an absorption spectroscopy experiment include the optics used to direct the radiation and the means of holding or containing the sample material (called a cuvette or cell).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For most UV, visible, and NIR measurements the use of precision quartz cuvettes are necessary.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] In both cases, it is important to select materials that have relatively little absorption of their own in the wavelength range of interest.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] The absorption of other materials could interfere with or mask the absorption from the sample.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/absorption-spectra] For instance, in several wavelength ranges it is necessary to measure the sample under vacuum or in a noble gas environment because gases in the atmosphere have interfering absorption features.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] In astrophysics, **accretion** is the accumulation of particles into a massive object by gravitationally attracting more matter, typically gaseous matter, into an accretion disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Most astronomical objects, such as galaxies, stars, and planets, are formed by accretion processes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion model that Earth and the other terrestrial planets formed from meteoric material was proposed in 1944 by Otto Schmidt, followed by the *protoplanet theory* of William McCrea (1960) and finally the *capture theory* of Michael Woolfson.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] In 1978, Andrew Prentice resurrected the initial Laplacian ideas about planet formation and developed the *modern Laplacian theory*.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] None of these models proved completely successful, and many of the proposed theories were descriptive.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The 1944 accretion model by Otto Schmidt was further developed in a quantitative way in 1969 by Viktor Safronov.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] He calculated, in detail, the different stages of terrestrial planet formation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Since then, the model has been further developed using intensive numerical simulations to study planetesimal accumulation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] It is now accepted that stars form by the gravitational collapse of interstellar gas.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Prior to collapse, this gas is mostly in the form of molecular clouds, such as the Orion Nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As the cloud collapses, losing potential energy, it heats up, gaining kinetic energy, and the conservation of angular momentum ensures that the cloud forms a flattened disk—the accretion disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] A few hundred thousand years after the Big Bang, the Universe cooled to the point where atoms could form.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As the Universe continued to expand and cool, the atoms lost enough kinetic energy, and dark matter coalesced sufficiently, to form protogalaxies.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As further accretion occurred, galaxies formed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Galaxies grow through mergers and smooth gas accretion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion also occurs inside galaxies, forming stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Stars are thought to form inside giant clouds of cold molecular hydrogen — giant molecular clouds of roughly 300,000 *M*☉ and 65 light-years (20 pc) in diameter.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Over millions of years, giant molecular clouds are prone to collapse and fragmentation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] These fragments then form small, dense cores, which in turn collapse into stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The cores range in mass from a fraction to several times that of the Sun and are called protostellar (protosolar) nebulae.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Compare it with the particle number density of the air at the sea level — 2.8×1019/cm3 (4.6×1020/cu in).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The initial collapse of a solar-mass protostellar nebula takes around 100,000 years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Every nebula begins with a certain amount of angular momentum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Gas in the central part of the nebula, with relatively low angular momentum, undergoes fast compression and forms a hot hydrostatic (non-contracting) core containing a small fraction of the mass of the original nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] This core forms the seed of what will become a star.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As the collapse continues, conservation of angular momentum dictates that the rotation of the infalling envelope accelerates, which eventually forms a disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As the infall of material from the disk continues, the envelope eventually becomes thin and transparent and the young stellar object (YSO) becomes observable, initially in far-infrared light and later in the visible.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Around this time the protostar begins to fuse deuterium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] If the protostar is sufficiently massive (above 80 *M*J), hydrogen fusion follows.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Otherwise, if its mass is too low, the object becomes a brown dwarf.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] This birth of a new star occurs approximately 100,000 years after the collapse begins.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Objects at this stage are known as Class I protostars, which are also called young T Tauri stars, evolved protostars, or young stellar objects.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] By this time, the forming star has already accreted much of its mass; the total mass of the disk and remaining envelope does not exceed 10–20% of the mass of the central YSO.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] At the next stage, the envelope completely disappears, having been gathered up by the disk, and the protostar becomes a classical T Tauri star.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The latter have accretion disks and continue to accrete hot gas, which manifests itself by strong emission lines in their spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The former do not possess accretion disks.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Classical T Tauri stars evolve into weakly lined T Tauri stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] This happens after about 1 million years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The mass of the disk around a classical T Tauri star is about 1–3% of the stellar mass, and it is accreted at a rate of 10−7 to 10−9 *M*☉ per year.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] A pair of bipolar jets is usually present as well.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion explains all peculiar properties of classical T Tauri stars: strong flux in the emission lines (up to 100% of the intrinsic luminosity of the star), magnetic activity, photometric variability and jets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The emission lines actually form as the accreted gas hits the "surface" of the star, which happens around its magnetic poles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The jets are byproducts of accretion: they carry away excessive angular momentum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The classical T Tauri stage lasts about 10 million years (there are only a few examples of so-called Peter Pan disks, where the accretion continues to persist for much longer periods, sometimes lasting for more than 40 million years).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The disk eventually disappears due to accretion onto the central star, planet formation, ejection by jets, and photoevaporation by ultraviolet radiation from the central star and nearby stars.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] As a result, the young star becomes a weakly lined T Tauri star, which, over hundreds of millions of years, evolves into an ordinary Sun-like star, dependent on its initial mass.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Self-accretion of cosmic dust accelerates the growth of the particles into boulder-sized planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The more massive planetesimals accrete some smaller ones, while others shatter in collisions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion disks are common around smaller stars, stellar remnants in a close binary, or black holes surrounded by material (such as those at the centers of galaxies).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Some dynamics in the disk, such as dynamical friction, are necessary to allow orbiting gas to lose angular momentum and fall onto the central massive object.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Occasionally, this can result in stellar surface fusion (see Bondi accretion).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] In the formation of terrestrial planets or planetary cores, several stages can be considered.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] First, when gas and dust grains collide, they agglomerate by microphysical processes like van der Waals forces and electromagnetic forces, forming micrometer-sized particles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] During this stage, accumulation mechanisms are largely non-gravitational in nature.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] However, planetesimal formation in the centimeter-to-meter range is not well understood, and no convincing explanation is offered as to why such grains would accumulate rather than simply rebound.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Ward (1996) suggests that when slow moving grains collide, the very low, yet non-zero, gravity of colliding grains impedes their escape.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] It is also thought that grain fragmentation plays an important role replenishing small grains and keeping the disk thick, but also in maintaining a relatively high abundance of solids of all sizes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] A number of mechanisms have been proposed for crossing the 'meter-sized' barrier.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Local concentrations of pebbles may form, which then gravitationally collapse into planetesimals the size of large asteroids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] These concentrations can occur passively due to the structure of the gas disk, for example, between eddies, at pressure bumps, at the edge of a gap created by a giant planet, or at the boundaries of turbulent regions of the disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Or, the particles may take an active role in their concentration via a feedback mechanism referred to as a streaming instability.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] In a streaming instability the interaction between the solids and the gas in the protoplanetary disk results in the growth of local concentrations, as new particles accumulate in the wake of small concentrations, causing them to grow into massive filaments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Alternatively, if the grains that form due to the agglomeration of dust are highly porous their growth may continue until they become large enough to collapse due to their own gravity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The low density of these objects allows them to remain strongly coupled with the gas, thereby avoiding high velocity collisions which could result in their erosion or fragmentation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Grains eventually stick together to form mountain-size (or larger) bodies called planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Collisions and gravitational interactions between planetesimals combine to produce Moon-size planetary embryos (protoplanets) over roughly 0.1–1 million years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Finally, the planetary embryos collide to form planets over 10–100 million years.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The planetesimals are massive enough that mutual gravitational interactions are significant enough to be taken into account when computing their evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Growth is aided by orbital decay of smaller bodies due to gas drag, which prevents them from being stranded between orbits of the embryos.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Further collisions and accumulation lead to terrestrial planets or the core of giant planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] If the planetesimals formed via the gravitational collapse of local concentrations of pebbles, their growth into planetary embryos and the cores of giant planets is dominated by the further accretions of pebbles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion is aided by the gas drag felt by objects as they accelerate toward a massive body.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Gas drag slows the pebbles below the escape velocity of the massive body causing them to spiral toward and to be accreted by it.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion may accelerate the formation of planets by a factor of 1000 compared to the accretion of planetesimals, allowing giant planets to form before the dissipation of the gas disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] However, core growth via pebble accretion appears incompatible with the final masses and compositions of Uranus and Neptune.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Direct calculations indicate that, in a typical protoplanetary disk, the formation time of a giant planet via pebble accretion is comparable to the formation times resulting from planetesimal accretion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The formation of terrestrial planets differs from that of giant gas planets, also called Jovian planets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The particles that make up the terrestrial planets are made from metal and rock that condensed in the inner Solar System.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] However, Jovian planets began as large, icy planetesimals, which then captured hydrogen and helium gas from the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Differentiation between these two classes of planetesimals arises due to the frost line of the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Meteorites contain a record of accretion and impacts during all stages of asteroid origin and evolution; however, the mechanism of asteroid accretion and growth is not well understood.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Evidence suggests the main growth of asteroids can result from gas-assisted accretion of chondrules, which are millimeter-sized spherules that form as molten (or partially molten) droplets in space before being accreted to their parent asteroids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] In the inner Solar System, chondrules appear to have been crucial for initiating accretion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The tiny mass of asteroids may be partly due to inefficient chondrule formation beyond 2 AU, or less-efficient delivery of chondrules from near the protostar.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Also, impacts controlled the formation and destruction of asteroids, and are thought to be a major factor in their geological evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Chondrules, metal grains, and other components likely formed in the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] These accreted together to form parent asteroids.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Some of these bodies subsequently melted, forming metallic cores and olivine-rich mantles; others were aqueously altered.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] After the asteroids had cooled, they were eroded by impacts for 4.5 billion years, or disrupted.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] For accretion to occur, impact velocities must be less than about twice the escape velocity, which is about 140 m/s (460 ft/s) for a 100 km (60 mi) radius asteroid.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Simple models for accretion in the asteroid belt generally assume micrometer-sized dust grains sticking together and settling to the midplane of the nebula to form a dense layer of dust, which, because of gravitational forces, was converted into a disk of kilometer-sized planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] But, several arguments suggest that asteroids may not have accreted this way.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Comets, or their precursors, formed in the outer Solar System, possibly millions of years before planet formation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] How and when comets formed is debated, with distinct implications for Solar System formation, dynamics, and geology.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Three-dimensional computer simulations indicate the major structural features observed on cometary nuclei can be explained by pairwise low velocity accretion of weak cometesimals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The currently favored formation mechanism is that of the nebular hypothesis, which states that comets are probably a remnant of the original planetesimal "building blocks" from which the planets grew.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Astronomers think that comets originate in both the Oort cloud and the scattered disk.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Because the scattered disk is dynamically active and the Kuiper belt relatively dynamically stable, the scattered disk is now seen as the most likely point of origin for periodic comets.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The classic Oort cloud theory states that the Oort cloud, a sphere measuring about 50,000 AU (0.24 pc) in radius, formed at the same time as the solar nebula and occasionally releases comets into the inner Solar System as a giant planet or star passes nearby and causes gravitational disruptions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Examples of such comet clouds may already have been seen in the Helix Nebula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] The *Rosetta* mission to comet 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko determined in 2015 that when Sun's heat penetrates the surface, it triggers evaporation (sublimation) of buried ice.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] While some of the resulting water vapour may escape from the nucleus, 80% of it recondenses in layers beneath the surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] This observation implies that the thin ice-rich layers exposed close to the surface may be a consequence of cometary activity and evolution, and that global layering does not necessarily occur early in the comet's formation history.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] While most scientists thought that all the evidence indicated that the structure of nuclei of comets is processed rubble piles of smaller ice planetesimals of a previous generation, the *Rosetta* mission confirmed the idea that comets are "rubble piles" of disparate material.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/accretion-astrophysics] Comets appear to have formed as ~100-km bodies, then overwhelmingly ground/recontacted into their present states.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China (the Minnan Golden Triangle) and Taiwan.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur dioxide pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] FGD gypsum is used in construction materials (e.g. concrete), and instead of natural gypsum it can be added to agricultural soils as a source of high-quality sulfur and calcium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles, but measures are required to further reduce road transport emissions, more especially in Diesel vehicles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Acid rain is now as severe a threat to the developing world, especially India and China, as it was earlier to some of the developed countries.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The purpose was to combat long-range transboundary air pollution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulphur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the Convention.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by emissions of particulate matter and sulphur dropping by 30-80% since 1990 in Europe and by 30-40% in North America.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of atmospheric pollution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Activity of the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Philippines, South Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emission allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emission allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] However, ethical arguments have been opposed to the ongoing rise of emissions trading, focusing on commodification of the atmosphere, pricing that which should not be priced, or civic responsibility.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/acid-deposition] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:atmosphere-of-earth/atmosphere-of-earth] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
